:INFO
My Position on Moby Dick and Why I Hold It
Moby Dick is two books bound together. The first is one of the great American \
novels: a study in obsession, leadership, and the cost of pursuing something \
that does not care whether you exist. The second is a detailed scientific \
treatise on whaling published in 1851. Both are genuinely present. The first \
book is worth every page. The second book is Melville testing whether you \
want the first book enough to earn it. My position is that you should read \
the whole thing and I will defend that position.

:NOTE.half
The cetology chapters are a patience tax Melville collects before the payoff.
|
